A SHORT HISTORY OF ST. PETERSBURG

St. Petersburg is one of the most important cultural and historical cities in Russia. 
It was founded in 1703 by Tsar Peter the Great during the Great Northern War. 
Peter wanted a modern European-style city that would connect Russia with Europe, 
so he built it on the Neva River near the Baltic Sea.

In 1712, St. Petersburg became the capital of the Russian Empire, replacing Moscow. 
The city quickly developed into a major center of politics, culture, and architecture.

During World War I, the city’s name was changed from St. Petersburg to Petrograd 
because the original name sounded too German. In 1924, after the death of Vladimir Lenin, 
the city was renamed Leningrad.

A major event in its history was the Siege of Leningrad during World War II (1941–1944). 
The city was surrounded by Nazi forces for nearly 900 days. Despite extreme famine and 
hardship, the city never surrendered.

In 1991, after the collapse of the Soviet Union, the city returned to its original 
name, St. Petersburg.

Today, St. Petersburg is known as Russia’s cultural capital. It is famous for its 
historic architecture, canals, museums, theaters, and rich artistic heritage.